  "case_id": "D2N197",
  "method": "cap",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports headaches that have been worsening lately, with occasional occurrences but increasingly frequent. She admits to sometimes forgetting to take her lisinopril medication, particularly on weekends. Her blood sugar has been running at 120 and 100. The patient reports that her blood pressure readings have been running high, with readings of 160/87 and 175/92. She rates the initial headache as 7 out of 10, and after taking Tylenol, it decreases to 4-5 out of 10. The patient reports having headaches and tenderness right here, and reports that she has tenderness on her cheek bones. The patient reports that she has not actually had any runny nose or congestion along with the headache.\n\nO:\nBlood pressure is mildly low. Heart rate is within normal limits. Neurologic examination is nonfocal. The patient has tenderness right here. The patient has tenderness on her cheek bones.\n\nA:\nThe patient's symptoms are consistent with a headache, hypertension, and possible diabetes. Further investigation is needed to determine the underlying cause and optimize management.\n\nP:\nThe doctor will increase the patient's lisinopril dose to 40 mg once daily. The doctor will order blood tests. The doctor will provide diabetes education to the patient. The doctor will follow up if symptoms worsen or do not improve.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nHeadache.\n\nMEDICAL HISTORY\n\nPatient reports history of hypertension and diabetes. She has migraines rarely every 1 to 2 years.\n\nSOCIAL HISTORY\n\nPatient reports she walks for exercise.\n\nALLERGIES\n\nPatient reports history of seasonal allergies.\n\nMEDICATIONS\n\nPatient reports taking lisinopril 20 mg once a day and Tylenol.\n\nREVIEW OF SYSTEMS\n\nHENT: Denies congestion or runny nose.\nRespiratory: Denies cough.\nGenitourinary: Denies polyuria.\nNeurological: Reports headaches.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nHead and Face\n- No frontal or maxillary sinus tenderness.\n\nNeck\n- General Examination: Neck is supple without lymphadenopathy.\n\nHematology/Lymphatic/Immunology\n- Palpation: No enlarged lymph nodes.\n\nASSESSMENT AND PLAN\n\n1. Hypertension with headaches.\n- Medical Reasoning: Patient presents today with complaints of increasing headaches and elevated blood pressure readings at home.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: We discussed it is safe for her to exercise and she has been encouraged to continue her walking program.\n- Medical Treatment: Patient will continue to take Tylenol for pain management. Her lisinopril was increased to 40 mg once a day. Routine blood work was ordered for further evaluation. She will also continue monitoring her blood pressure at home.\n\n2. Diabetes.\n- Medical Reasoning: Patient has been experiencing slightly elevated glucose levels with her home monitoring.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: She was provided with diabetic education which she will review.\n- Medical Treatment: Hemoglobin A1c was ordered.\n\nPatient Agreements: The patient understands and agrees with the recommended medical treatment plan.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nPatient will return for follow-up to see myself or Dr. Ruth to review her lab work and further treatment plan to get her blood pressure under control.",
